# Writing style

<!-- BEGIN: shared writing-style (synced from clause-dev/.shared/writing-style-fragment.md — do not edit in place) -->

## Tone

Low-ego, factual, expert-to-expert. No marketing speak, no hype, no cheerleading. Describe what it does, not how great it is.

## Top of document

The first three or four sections or paragraphs are prose that frames the piece. Lists, feature dumps, bulleted TLDRs, and similar structural content come after the framing. A document that opens with a flat bulleted list reads as a TLDR dump, not a considered piece.

Exceptions allowed at the top:

- Round-artifact metadata (`**Date:** / **Phase:** / **Scope:** / **Source topics:**`) inside `mock/design_rounds/` files.
- Tables with at least two columns and at least three rows of real content. Parallel-column information belongs in parallel-column form; single-column or two-row "tables" are prose wearing a costume.
- Table of Contents. If a TOC exists, it must be section one or two, never buried lower.

## Punctuation

Em-dashes (`—`) sparingly. Appropriate for emphasis or a parenthetical aside where a comma is too quiet and parens too heavy. Wrong when a period, colon, semicolon, or parens would carry the same load without interrupting the reader. Overuse smell: more than one per roughly ten lines of prose. Replace most with periods, commas, or parens.

No exclamation marks in prose. Semicolons sparingly to link two tightly related independent clauses; when in doubt, use a period. Colons introduce lists, quotes, or clarifying phrases, not mid-sentence separators.

## Word choice

No hype words: "blazing", "seamless", "powerful", "amazing", "incredible", "game-changing", "best-in-class".

No corporate jargon: "leverage" becomes "use", "utilize" becomes "use", "unlock" becomes "enable" or the specific action, "streamline" becomes a description of what was removed. "Synergy", "holistic", "paradigm", "robust", "scalable" as loose adjectives: cut or replace with a verifiable claim.

No greeting openers: "Sure!", "Happy to help!", "Let me explain". Public docs are read by someone with a goal; state the first fact.

No filler: "it should be noted that", "essentially", "basically", "at the end of the day", "for all intents and purposes".

## Emoji

None in public prose. Only exception: semantic UI mocks or diagrams where an emoji carries information a word cannot.

## Lists

Good for hierarchical content, genuine enumeration, and ordered steps. Long-form bullets with real content are fine; a bullet with three sentences is a structured paragraph.

Forbidden everywhere: bullets of the form `- <label>: <short description>`. The label-plus-colon form is cheat-sheet, not writing. Use a glossary table or prose instead.

Forbidden at the top of a document: flat single-line bulleted lists without hierarchy. (Exceptions above apply.)

Prefer ordered lists when order matters, unordered otherwise.

## Doc comments and inline comments (Rust)

`///` for items, `//!` for modules. First line is a brief summary under about 80 characters, because it renders into rustdoc index pages. Empty line, then details.

Inline comments explain why, not what; the code already tells the reader what.

```rust
/// A resolved handle to a registered entry.
///
/// Handles are resolved once at construction and reused across
/// lookups.
pub struct Handle { ... }

// offset because the catalogue is 0-indexed but display is 1-indexed
let display_idx = idx + 1;
```

## Error messages

State the problem and the fix. Name the types, values, and operations involved. Name the remediation.

```rust
// Bad
Error: width out of range

// Good
Error: UFixed<{I}, {F}> with S = Hot requires I + F <= 64 (Hot
container is u64 max). Use S = Warm or Precise for wider logical
width.
```

## Headings

Title Case for the top-level `#` (document title). Sentence case for `##` and below. Imperative or nominal, not interrogative.

## Commit messages

Format: `type: lowercase imperative message`. Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`. Breaking: `feat!:` / `refactor!:`. No parentheses, no capitals, no trailing period. Under 72 characters for the subject line. Body optional; explain why, not what.

## Enforcement scope

Rules apply to every piece of written content in the repo. The difference is automation, not standard.

Public-facing docs are gated at commit and push: `mock/PRINCIPLES.md.tmpl`, `mock/DESIGN.md.tmpl`, `mock/WORKFLOW.md.tmpl`, `README.md`, `mock/crates/**/*.md.tmpl`, `mock/agent/**/*.md.tmpl`, Rust doc and inline comments under `crates/**/*.rs`. The gate flags runaway em-dash density, leading-paragraph lists, hype words, exclamation marks in prose, and the banned jargon. Single-occurrence use passes; runaway usage blocks.

Round artifacts under `mock/design_rounds/` and research notes follow the same rules as a matter of discipline but are not gated.

